dataset_name: NYCHA Resident Jobs Programs and Training

frequent_values: • Job development, placement and retention/advancement support.
• Ability to perform eight (8) hours of physical work each day"
• Job readiness, job search assistance and training.

longest_values: You will be greeted by REES staff and asked to attend a short presentation where you will receive an overview of all of REES’ available services, which include referrals for employment, training, GED and ESOL classes available through a NYCHA Community Center, financial counseling, and appointments to attend the Test of Adult Basic Education (T.A.B.E.), which is the first step in the application process for the NYCHA Resident Training Academy (NRTA). "
Serving residents of Betances, Moore Houses and East 152nd Street-Courtlandt Houses the South Bronx.
• Ability to score a 6.0 reading and math level on the Test of Adult Basic Education (T.A.B.E.)
Documents Needed for Your Appointment: Valid photo ID (examples include: a DMV issued ID)"
• The strengthening of social ties among residents and community stakeholders to support

frequent_values: The NYCHA Resident Training Academy (NRTA) provides employment-linked training opportunities and job placement assistance to NYCHA residents in the construction, pest control, maintenance, and janitorial fields. The NRTA works with successful graduates of the Academy to provide job placement assistance by focusing on jobs with career paths. Past NRTA graduates have obtained jobs at NYCHA in positions such as Caretakers and Pest Control Technicians, and with NYCHA contractors and affordable housing developers in the various construction trades.

Jobs-Plus is an employment program that was created to work with all working-age residents in designated public housing developments or a cluster of developments.  The goal of the Jobs-Plus program is to raise the levels of employment and earnings among New York City public housing communities.  Services are limited only to residents who live in a Jobs-Plus designated development.

shortest_values: To receive services, you must be an authorized NYCHA resident.

NYCHA’s Office of Resident Economic Empowerment & Sustainability (REES) develops and implements programs, policies and collaborations to measurably support residents’ increased economic opportunities with a focus on employment and advancement, financial literacy and asset building, adult education and training, and business development.
